# The VecP Labs Transformer Architecture Challenge

**Hosted by David Cappelli — VecP Labs LLC**
**Tool: [VecP Labs Transformer Simulator](https://vecplabs.github.io/transformer-simulator)**

---

## Overview

Three AI models — Claude (Anthropic), Grok (xAI), and Gemini (Google) — each design a sub-500M parameter transformer architecture using the VecP Labs Transformer Simulator. Each model must also specify its complete training configuration and select its training corpus. All three designs are then trained for 7,500 steps on identical hardware and scored against shared evaluation benchmarks.

This is not a prompt engineering contest. This is a test of whether an AI model actually understands transformer mechanics well enough to make informed, defensible architectural decisions under real-world constraints.

---

## Rules

### Hardware Constraint
All designs must train on a single **NVIDIA RTX 4070 Ti Super (16 GB VRAM)** with 64 GB system RAM (Ryzen 5600). If your architecture does not fit in 16 GB VRAM during training, it is disqualified.

### Parameter Budget
**500 million parameters maximum.** There is no minimum. Parameter efficiency is part of the scoring — using fewer parameters to achieve competitive loss is rewarded, not penalized.

### Training Budget
All models are trained for exactly **7,500 steps**. No more, no less.

### Training Configuration
Each competitor specifies their own complete training configuration as part of their submission. This includes but is not limited to:

- Batch size (must fit in 16 GB VRAM)
- Learning rate and schedule (warmup, decay, cosine, etc.)
- Optimizer and its hyperparameters
- Gradient accumulation steps (if any)
- Sequence length
- Precision (fp16, bf16, mixed, etc.)
- Any other training hyperparameters

Training configuration is part of the architecture. A good designer knows how to train their model, not just draw it. Poor training config choices will show up in the loss curve.

### Training Data
Each competitor selects their own training corpus and must justify the choice in their design document. The corpus must be:

- **Publicly available** (no proprietary datasets)
- **Downloadable** (David has to actually obtain it)
- **Clearly specified** (exact dataset name, split, any filtering or preprocessing steps)

Corpus selection is a first-class design decision. You are choosing what your model learns from.

### Submission Format
Each competitor submits two deliverables:

1. **Transformer Simulator JSON export** — the architecture as built in the VecP Labs Transformer Simulator (vecplabs.github.io/transformer-simulator). The simulator supports primitive-level editing, drag-reorderable components, and versioned JSON import/export.

2. **Design document** — a written explanation covering:
   - Architectural thesis: What is the core idea behind this design? What problem does it solve or what tradeoff does it navigate?
   - Layer-by-layer rationale: Why this depth, this width, this head configuration, this FFN ratio?
   - Training configuration rationale: Why these hyperparameters?
   - Corpus rationale: Why this data, and how does it interact with the architecture?
   - Compute analysis: Chinchilla token count awareness, expected FLOP budget, VRAM utilization estimate
   - Known risks: What could go wrong? Where are the design's weak points?

