## Competition Rulings (Post-Submission Addendum)

*Issued after independent third-party audits of all three submissions.*

### Ruling 1 — Strict As-Submitted Scoring

**Phase 1 (Design Evaluation) scores are locked on what was submitted.** No corrections, no revisions, no second drafts. The design document and simulator export are scored exactly as received.

If your parameter count is wrong, that's scored. If your VRAM estimate would OOM, that's scored. If your training config is missing critical flags, that's scored. Phase 1 tests whether you can design a system that works *on paper* — and getting the paper wrong is a design failure.

Rationale: The entire point of Phase 1 is to evaluate engineering rigor at the design stage. Allowing post-audit corrections would reward models that submit first drafts and iterate based on feedback rather than models that get it right the first time. An architect who miscalculates load-bearing capacity doesn't get to revise the blueprint after the structural engineer catches it and still get full marks.

### Ruling 2 — Config Adjustment for Training

Despite strict Phase 1 scoring, **all three models will be trained.** The host (David) reserves the right to adjust training configurations to fit the hardware reality:

- If a submission would OOM as specified, the config will be adjusted to the minimum changes necessary to fit in 16 GB VRAM (e.g., reducing micro-batch size, enforcing gradient checkpointing, capping sequence length).
- If a submission's training time would exceed reasonable bounds (~40–50 hours), the config may be adjusted to bring wall-clock time into parity with other submissions.
- All adjustments will be documented and disclosed alongside Phase 2 results.

**Adjusted configs do not retroactively improve Phase 1 scores.** The adjustment exists solely to ensure Phase 2 (Empirical Performance) can occur for all competitors. A model whose config required adjustment competes in Phase 2 with whatever architecture it actually has — but the record shows it needed intervention to run.

Rationale: Disqualifying a submission on config errors would eliminate the most interesting part of the challenge — seeing whether the *architecture itself* has merit despite sloppy engineering. The empirical results may vindicate or condemn the design independent of the config mistakes.

### Ruling 3 — Fresh Restart Protocol

Between each training run, the host machine will undergo a **full restart cycle:**

- Complete system reboot (not just process termination)
- CUDA cache fully cleared
- No residual GPU memory allocation from previous runs
- Identical system state at the start of each training run

This ensures no competitor benefits from (or is penalized by) memory fragmentation, orphaned CUDA contexts, or thermal throttling artifacts from a prior run.

### Ruling 4 — Evaluation Context Standardization

All models are evaluated on the shared benchmarks (Wikitext-103 test, C4 validation) using a **standardized evaluation context length of 1024 tokens**, regardless of training sequence length. Models trained at longer context lengths may benefit from their training, but the evaluation playing field is level.

